Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in table understanding lies not only in recognizing individual cell contents but in identifying semantically coherent multi-word units that span across substructures within a single cell—such as "New York City" in a cell meant to represent a location, or "Revenue (in millions)" as a compound header. Existing methods either treat cells as flat token sequences (losing internal layout cues) or focus on inter-cell structural relationships while underutilizing intra-cell spatial and typographic signals. Inspired by Paper 1’s structure-aware equivariance and visual-layout sensitivity, Paper 2’s hypergraph modeling for boundary detection, and Paper 3’s emphasis on functional grouping through neuro-symbolic reasoning, I propose a novel framework that explicitly models *intra-cell* semantic unit formation via **visual-token graphs**. Unlike prior work that aggregates tokens into cells post-hoc, this idea treats each cell as a micro-document where textual tokens are nodes connected by visual proximity, font style, and alignment edges. By applying self-supervised contrastive learning over plausible semantic units derived from these graphs, the model learns to segment and embed meaningful phrases—even without explicit annotations. This approach uniquely bridges low-level OCR-level tokenization with high-level semantic coherence, enabling downstream models to interpret complex cell content more accurately. It differs from previous efforts by shifting focus from inter-cell to *intra-cell* structure, introducing graph-based relational reasoning at a granular level, and leveraging self-supervision to avoid costly labeling of phrase boundaries.

