  "Idea": "Current document AI systems often fail to parse semantically meaningful phrases embedded within individual table cells because they assume uniform tokenization or ignore fine-grained spatial layout. For example, a cell may contain 'Q4 2023 Results' in bold followed by '$5.2M' below it, yet standard models process this as a linear string, missing the internal segmentation between label and value. To address this, we propose a new method called Visual-Token Graphs (VTG) for Layout-Aware Semantic Unit Discovery. Our approach treats each table cell independently as a structured mini-document composed of OCR-derived text tokens annotated with positional, font, and alignment features. Within each cell, we construct a dynamic graph where nodes are word pieces (e.g., BPE tokens), and edges encode visual proximity, shared formatting (bold/italic), horizontal alignment, and whitespace gaps. A graph neural network then learns to cluster these tokens into coherent semantic units—such as headers, values, units, or parenthetical modifiers—by predicting which subsets form functionally unified expressions. Crucially, we introduce a self-supervised objective based on masked semantic unit modeling: during training, random plausible units (detected heuristically via formatting clusters) are masked, and the model must reconstruct them using contextual and visual cues. This avoids reliance on manual phrase-level annotations. The resulting embeddings can be injected into larger table understanding pipelines (e.g., TAPAS, LayoutLMv3) to improve performance on tasks like fact verification, table-to-text generation, or entity linking. We evaluate our method on modified versions of ToTTo, SQA, and our newly curated VTG-FUNSD dataset—a version of FUNSD augmented with intra-cell phrase boundaries. We expect significant gains in both unit discovery F1 and downstream task accuracy, especially in tables with rich formatting. This work fills a critical gap: while much research focuses on row/column structure, little attention has been paid to how meaning emerges from layout *within* cells. By formalizing this problem and providing a scalable solution, we enable more nuanced interpretation of real-world documents such as financial reports, scientific tables, and invoices.",
