  "Experiment": "Our experimental plan unfolds in five phases. Phase 1: Dataset construction. We curate TabularPhrases-1K, a new dataset of 1,000 complex PDF tables from financial reports and academic papers, annotated with both intra-cell phrase boundaries and cross-cell functional roles (e.g., label/value/modifier). We also generate synthetic variants with permuted rows/columns to test structural robustness. Phase 2: Hypergraph construction. From OCR outputs (via DonutOCR or LayoutParser), we extract tokens with bounding boxes, font styles, and line breaks. Within each cell, we apply clustering (DBSCAN + formatting thresholds) to propose initial intra-cell units. Across cells, we detect recurring spatial-formatting motifs (e.g., right-aligned numbers below bold text) to form inter-cell hyperedges. Phase 3: Model architecture. HyPER employs a dual-level hypergraph neural network: first, a local GNN processes intra-cell edges using node features (text embeddings, font, position); then, a hypergraph convolution layer aggregates information over hyperedges using learnable incidence weights. Equivariant attention ensures that permutations of structurally equivalent units do not alter output semantics. Phase 4: Pre-training and fine-tuning. We train using Masked Hyperedge Modeling: random hyperedges are masked, and the model reconstructs constituent tokens and their roles. A contrastive loss encourages consistency among semantically aligned units. We then fine-tune on table-to-text generation (ToTTo), fact verification (SQA), and entity linking (extended FUNSD). Phase 5: Evaluation. Metrics include hyperedge recovery F1, BLEU/ROUGE for generation, and QA accuracy. Baselines include VTG, LayoutLMv3, and HGALayoutLM. We expect >18% improvement in phrase-level recall and ≥4 BLEU gain, especially in highly formatted tables. We will release code, model checkpoints, and TabularPhrases-1K to foster further research.",
